Fantasy Football Projections: CMSC320 Final Tutorial¶

by Amal Verma¶

American Football is by far the most popular sport in the United States. Every year, the 32 teams spread across the United States of America play against each other all with the hopes of winning the Super Bowl at the end of the season. And every year, people from all around the world tune in to watch these games and cheer for their favorite teams. In fact, the National Football League, the most popular American professional football league, has the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.

With such a dedicated fanbase, it is no wonder that there are so many fan games associated with the sport. One of the most popular games is Fantasy Football. Fantasy Football is a game that allows you to be the owner, General Manager and coach of your very own football team. In this game, a group of people get together and draft a team made up of NFL players. This way every team in the fantasy league has different players. Then, based on a NFL player's on-field performance in a given week, the person with that MFL player on their team scores points. The person whose team ends up having a higher total points by the end of the week wins the week. Each week a person goes against a different person's team. If a NFL player is struggling, a person can release him, just like in the real NFL. A person can also trade with other teams. And if no one has a NFL player on their team, they are available to be added to a person's roster from the waiver wire. Just like the real NFL, every Fantasy league has a postseason as well. The fantasy playoffs are usually played from Weeks 14-16. In the final week, a champion is crowned!

In this tutorial, I hope to be able to accurately predict how well a player will perform in fantasy football based on their past years' data. If this tutorial works out well, people can use this model to better draft players in their own fantasy football teams. If people can use this model to figure out how well a player will perform for their fantasy team, they can better prioritize their draft picks. Now obviously this model can not account for external factors, such as injuries that may occur during a season, however the model should be able to pick up trends based on age, time period, and other statistics to accurately assess potential for most players. Now since football has many different positions with many different roles, I will focus on certain positions to see which players have the most potential for their respective position. The positions I will be focussing on are Quarterbacks, Runningbacks, and Wide Recievers.

First, I will first need to create a data frame with all the quarterback information from all the years from 1992 to 2019 inclusive. The reason I chose to start at 1992 is because fantasy football has changed drastically over the years, and while this will be helpful in determining how future years will play out, the NFL did not start tracking Targets until 1992. Since I wanted to see if this attribute played a significant role in Fantasy Points, I wanted to use data that included this attribute, and therefore I started at 1992. The reason I ended at 2019 is because that is when the data I chose ended.

The data set I used can be downloaded from https://www.fantasyfootballdatapros.com/csv_files. I downloaded Fantasy Stats by clicking the button that said "Download Fantasy Stats."

In the above code, I had different data sets for every year, so I had to combine all the data sets into one major data set. In order to do this, I first created an array object in which I would store all of the indivual year data as data frames. Then I created a for loop that would go through every CSV file I had and create a data frame with the data in each file. In the same for loop I would also append the data frame that was created into the array object I created before the for loop. At the end of the for loop I had populated the entire array with data frame corresponding to data from the years 1992 to 2019 inclusive. I then concatenated all the lists in the array together to create one big data frame with all the data across all the years, and I made sure to have a year attribute so that it was obvious which data came from which year, since I was also going to see if year played a factor in fantasy points.

Explaining the Columns/Attributes¶

Player: Has the player name is the form "Firstname Lastname"
Team: Has a 3 letter abbreviation for the team the player is on during the year
Position: Has the 2 letter abbreviation for the position the player plays (QB, RB, TE, WR)
Age: Has the age of the player during the year
Games: Number of games a player had during the year
GameStarted: Number of games a player started in during the year
Completions: Number of times a player has thrown a ball and the ball was caught by a teammate during the year
PassingAttempts: Number of passes a player makes during the year
PassingYards: Total number of yards a player a thrown a completed ball during the year
InterceptionsThrown: Total number of times a player has thrown a ball to the other team during the year
RushingAttempts: Total number of times a player tried to run the ball during the year
RushingYards: Total number of yards a player has run the ball during the year
Targets: Total number of times a player has been thrown the ball to during the year
Receptions: Total number of times a player has caught the ball during the year
ReceivingYards: Total number of yards a player caught the ball from during the year
Yards per Reception: ReceivingYards divided by Receptions for a player
Fumbles: Number of times a player drops the ball during the year
FumblesLost: Number of times a player drops the ball during the year and the other team gets the ball
PassingTD: Number of times a player passed a ball to a player and the player got a touchdown
RushingTD: Number of times a player ran the ball into the touchdown
ReceivingTD: Number of times a player caught the ball and got a touchdown
FantasyPoints: The amount of fantasy points a player got during the year
Year: The current year

qb = [] # store qb averages per year
rb = [] # store rb averages per year
te = [] # store te averages per year
wr = [] # store wr averages per year
for year in fantasy_df.Year.unique():
    tot_qb = 0
    count_qb = 0
    tot_rb = 0
    count_rb = 0
    tot_te = 0
    count_te = 0
    tot_wr = 0
    count_wr = 0
    for row in range(len(fantasy_df)):
        if fantasy_df.iloc[row]['Position'] == 'QB':
            tot_qb = tot_qb + fantasy_df.iloc[row]['FantasyPoints']
            count_qb = count_qb + 1
        elif fantasy_df.iloc[row]['Position'] == 'RB':
            tot_rb = tot_rb + fantasy_df.iloc[row]['FantasyPoints']
            count_rb = count_rb + 1
        elif fantasy_df.iloc[row]['Position'] == 'TE':
            tot_te = tot_te + fantasy_df.iloc[row]['FantasyPoints']
            count_te = count_te + 1
        elif fantasy_df.iloc[row]['Position'] == 'WR':
            tot_wr = tot_wr + fantasy_df.iloc[row]['FantasyPoints']
            count_wr = count_wr + 1
    qb.append(tot_qb/count_qb)
    rb.append(tot_rb/count_rb)
    te.append(tot_te/count_te)
    wr.append(tot_wr/count_wr)

plt.scatter(fantasy_df.Year.unique(), rb, label = "RB")
plt.scatter(fantasy_df.Year.unique(), te, label = "TE")
plt.scatter(fantasy_df.Year.unique(), wr, label = "WR")

Quarterbacks¶

The first position we will be focussing on is the quarterback position. In football, every team only has one quarterback on the field at a time. The quarterback is an offensive position, and the role of the quarterback for the team is to throw the ball to the wide recievers or hand the ball off to the running backs. There are also times the quarterback runs the ball themselves.

Hypothesis Testing¶

The plots above only show current fantasy points with respect to one attribute at a time. My question however is to see if I can predict a quarterback's points in the next year based on his current years performance. In order to do this I will try to see if I can fit a linear regression model on this data. A linear regression model firstly assumes that the relationship between the independent variable(s) and the mean of the dependent variable is linear. The dependent variable is the number of Fantasy Points a player will get in the next year, while the independent variables I hope to test are all the attributes: 'Age', 'Games', 'GameStarted', 'Completions', 'PassingAttempts', 'PassingYards', 'InterceptionsThrown', 'RushingAttempts', 'RushingYards', 'Targets', 'Receptions', 'ReceivingYards', 'Yards per Reception', 'Fumbles', 'FumblesLost', 'PassingTD', 'RushingTD', 'ReceivingTD', 'Year'. I will be testing these attributes and whatever attributes are not significant, I will remove from the regression model. My null hypothesis will be that all of the attributes are insignificant (AKA there is no relationship between a certain attribute and a quarterback's fantasy points in the next year), meaning if the coefficients in my linear regression model correpsonding to certain attributes have a p-value of 0.05 or less, I will reject the null hypothesis and use the attributes in my linear regression model. This means my alternative hypothesis would be that there does exist a relationship between a certain attribute and a quarterback's fantasy points in the next year.

A linear regression model also assumes that observations are independent of each other. In the case of this data, the observations are independent of one another because the data is collected on different people. Furthermore, a linear regression model assumes that for any fixed value of the independent variable, the dependent variable is normally distributed. Lastly, a linear regression model assumes that the variance of residual is the same for any value of the independent variable. These are the assumptions I am making when trying to fit a linear regression model on this data.

Source: https://sphweb.bumc.bu.edu/otlt/MPH-Modules/BS/R/R5_Correlation-Regression/R5_Correlation-Regression4.html

Looking at the table above, it appears that all of the attributes are significant because they all have p-values less than 0.05. This means the linear regression model is:
NextYearFantasyPoints = 102.826 - 2.227 x age - 2.052 x games - 0.239 x passing_attempts + 0.061 x passing_yards + 0.118 x rushing_yards + 2.658 x passing_touchdowns

This means that age negatively impacts future performance, which I predicted would happen because athletes tend to play worse on average as they age. It also appears that the number of games they played in the previous season negatively impacts their future performance, perhaps because of the physicality of the sport and the wear and tear a player's body goes through during a game. It also appears as though the passing attempts negatively impacts future performance, but the passing yards, rushing yards, and passing touch downs all positively impact future performance.

Now let's test this regression model on the testing set. We already know that for the training data, the model has an R-squared score of 0.469. This means that 46.9 percent of the variance in the dependent variable is explained by the model for the training data.

Insights¶

In [122]:
predicted = fit.predict(ind_test)

Now that we have the predictions of the depedent variables based off of the independent variables from the test set, we can compare it with the actual values of the dependent variable from the test set. There are three primary metrics used to evaluate linear models. These are: Mean absolute error (MAE), Mean squared error (MSE), or Root mean squared error (RMSE). We will look at all three.

The mean absolute error represents the average error.

The mean squared error is similar to the mean absolute error but it noise is exaggerated and larger errors have more of an emphasis.

The Root mean squared error is the mean squared error with the result square rooted.

Source: https://towardsdatascience.com/linear-regression-in-python-9a1f5f000606

In [123]:
# Mean absolute error
met.mean_absolute_error(predicted, dep_test)
Out[123]:
60.014956865491065
In [124]:
# Mean squared error
met.mean_squared_error(predicted, dep_test)
Out[124]:
5877.631071373903
In [125]:
# Root mean absolute error
np.sqrt(met.mean_squared_error(predicted, dep_test))
Out[125]:
76.66570987980157

Based on the above metrics, the mean absolute error means that on average the actual fantasy points a player gets in a following year is 60.01 points away from what the linear regression model predicts for the test set. Since the root mean absolute error is greater than the mean absolute error, this means that the data is concentrated away from the linear regression model. This means that while the linear regression model somewhat fits the data, and all of the coefficients and attributes used are significant for the model, the model is still not able to very accurately predict how well a quarterback will perform based on his previous year's performance. This is probably in large part due to the unpredictability of the sport, as well as the fact that everyone changes in different ways throughout the years. Maybe if I had more attributes besides just the pure football statistics in the data set, I could have created a more accurate model.

What was pretty surprising for me however was the fact that so many attributes that I thought would have mattered were deemed to be insignificant by the original linear regression model. For example, I knew age would have mattered because younger players have more room to grow than older players. However, I also thought time period would have mattered more because quarterbacks have started getting more points as the time period has increased, so I thought this would be reflected in the regression model. Also, I thought completions would have mattered more because that statistic in football is pretty dependent on the quarterback position. Maybe percent of passes completed would have been a better statistic though looking back.

Hypothesis Testing¶

The hypothesis test will be similar to the one conducted about quarterbacks. My question will be to see if I can predict a runningback's points in the next year based on his current years performance. I will one again try to see if I can fit a linear regression model on this data. The dependent variable will be the number of Fantasy Points a player will get in the next year, while the independent variables I hope to test will once again be all the attributes: 'Age', 'Games', 'GameStarted', 'Completions', 'PassingAttempts', 'PassingYards', 'InterceptionsThrown', 'RushingAttempts', 'RushingYards', 'Targets', 'Receptions', 'ReceivingYards', 'Yards per Reception', 'Fumbles', 'FumblesLost', 'PassingTD', 'RushingTD', 'ReceivingTD', 'Year'. I will be testing these attributes and whatever attributes are not significant, I will remove from the regression model. My null hypothesis will be that all of the attributes are insignificant (AKA there is no relationship between a certain attribute and a runningback's fantasy points in the next year), meaning if the coefficients in my linear regression model correpsonding to certain attributes have a p-value of 0.05 or less, I will reject the null hypothesis and use the attributes in my linear regression model. This means my alternative hypothesis would be that there does exist a relationship between a certain attribute and a runningback's fantasy points in the next year.

It appears all of the new attributes we used to create the regression model are significant because they all have a p-value that is less than 0.05. This means the final regresion model is:

RunningbackFantasyPoints = 117.2779 - 0.8473 x GamesStarted - 2.7455 x Age - 1.8582 x Games + 1.3990 x Receptions + 1.3572 x PassingYards + 0.1089 x RushingYards

This means that the number of games started, the age, and the number of games played all negatively impact future performance. This is probably for a similar reason as I stated for quarterbacks. It also appears that receptions, passing yards, and rushing yards all positively impact future performance.

Now let's test this regression model on the testing set. We already know that for the training data, the model has an R-squared score of 0.487. This means that 48.7 percent of the variance in the dependent variable is explained by the model for the training data.

Based on the above metrics, the mean absolute error means that on average the actual fantasy points a player gets in a following year is 50.97 points away from what the linear regression model predicts for the test set. Since the root mean absolute error is greater than the mean absolute error, this means that the data is concentrated away from the linear regression model. This means that while the linear regression model somewhat fits the data, and all of the coefficients and attributes used are significant for the model, the model is still not able to very accurately predict how well a runningback will perform based on his previous year's performance.

What was pretty surprising for me was that PassingYards were deemed significant for a runningback, but RushingAttempts and RushingYards were insignificant. This was surprising because runningbacks are a rushing-heavy role so I assumed those statistics would matter the most.

Hypothesis Testing¶

The hypothesis test will be similar to the one conducted about quarterbacks and runningbacks. My question will be to see if I can predict a wide receiver's points in the next year based on their current years performance. I will one again try to see if I can fit a linear regression model on this data. The dependent variable will be the number of Fantasy Points a player will get in the next year, while the independent variables I hope to test will once again be all the attributes: 'Age', 'Games', 'GameStarted', 'Completions', 'PassingAttempts', 'PassingYards', 'InterceptionsThrown', 'RushingAttempts', 'RushingYards', 'Targets', 'Receptions', 'ReceivingYards', 'Yards per Reception', 'Fumbles', 'FumblesLost', 'PassingTD', 'RushingTD', 'ReceivingTD', 'Year'. I will be testing these attributes and whatever attributes are not significant, I will remove from the regression model. My null hypothesis will be that all of the attributes are insignificant (AKA there is no relationship between a certain attribute and a wide receiver's fantasy points in the next year), meaning if the coefficients in my linear regression model correpsonding to certain attributes have a p-value of 0.05 or less, I will reject the null hypothesis and use the attributes in my linear regression model. This means my alternative hypothesis would be that there does exist a relationship between a certain attribute and a wide receiver's fantasy points in the next year.

Wrap up Thoughts¶

Looking at the models I created, there were a lot of similarities, such as the fact that age and games played always seemed to negatively impact performance, while the other attributes that were deemed significant always seemed to help the future fantasy points. In general, none of my models were all that accurate, but it is difficult to come up with an accurate model for this type of sport anyways because everyone is different and just because two people play the same position does not mean they will improve at the same rate based on their statistics. Also football is a very dangerous sport, and players are always getting injured. As a result, players who may perform very well during a previous year may not perform as well in a future year due to being injured. I tried to take these injury variables into account by attempting to factor in age, but just because a player is older than another player, it does not necessarily mean they are more prone to injury, it all depends on other factors. Maybe I could have created more accurate models if I had more statistics about different players, but that is just a way this tutorial can be improved upon in the future.

Besides that though, I felt like this was very enlightening to see how the model deemed certain features to be insignificant, when I really assumed they would have played a large role. For example, I would have thought Yards per Reception and Reception would have played a more vital role for predicting future performances of Wide Receivers, but it actually did not pan out to be significant, which really surprised me because they play such a vital role in a wide receiver's job in the sport.

I will love to see how these models pan out when I play fantasy next year though!
